Headlines.Author: Dave Kansas

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market tone: Relatively upbeat as commodity prices recover.Overnight action: Dollar higher; Treasurys lower; Nymex crude higher at $100.16; gold higher at $1506.28.Watch for: Conference Board's April Employment Trends Index due out at 10 a.m.The Breakfast BriefingAfter a tumultuous week, stocks look set to open higher today as key commodity prices recover and overseas markets build on Friday's gains in the U.S.Commodities went on a roller-coaster ride last week, with oil and silver plunging before recovering Friday. Silver lost 27% in the week, its worst weekly performance in 31 years. Nymex crude dropped 15%, its biggest drop since Dec. 2008. Both oil and silver are recovering this morning, but remain well off their highs.The skid in commodities prices has prompted widespread debate about whether or not stock markets need higher commodity prices to move higher. The immediate thinking is that commodities provide a "tell" about global growth. They go up, growth good. They go down, growth bad.But in the not-so-distant past, lower commodity prices helped drive shares higher, especially during the 1980s and 1990s. Moreover, some analysts now opine that lower energy prices in particular could give stocks a boost, especially if consumers find relief at the pump. That debate will get more air in the coming days, especially if commodities remain sluggish.The recent drop in commodities fed into present paradigm (growth bad) and soured the investor mood much of last week. Non-manufacturing survey data was weaker-than-expected and initial jobless claims spiked well above expectations, raising concerns about how the durability of the job-market's grinding recovery.The mixed economic data, capped by a surprisingly strong gain in April payrolls Friday, indicates that the economy may have slipped a gear, but not badly. And even the payrolls report had some confounding elements. While 244,000 jobs were added last month, the unemployment rate rose to 9% and one of the two employment surveys (the less reliable Household survey) showed a reduction in jobs for April.After surging on that news, stocks retreated from their highs Friday as the euro-zone debt crisis resurfaced and chatter of a Greek debt restructuring rose. The euro-zone debt situation will continue to percolate this week as eurocrats grapple with how to resolve Greece's forlorn fiscal situation and finalize Portugal's recue package. Expect euro-zone headlines to distract in the coming days.One overlooked factor slipping into the economic numbers and some less rosy second-quarter earnings outlooks is the fallout from the Japan earthquake. While the tragedy has moved to the background, its after-effects, especially in terms of supply-chain disruptions, continues to affect the technology and automotive sector.Earnings have moved off center stage, and most of the big companies have reported. Only 16 S&P 500 companies report this week, including Tyson today and Cisco on Wednesday. The reporting season has been robust, with 73% of S&P 500 companies beating earnings expectations and 68% beating revenue expectations. That helped buoy stock prices until the middle of last week.With earnings a bit scanter, expect focus to turn to economic issues more intently. The big reports this week come later, with April retail sales, weekly jobless claims and the PPI on Thursday. Friday brings the CPI. Last week's rapid retreat in commodities prices won't get captured in this week's headline figures, but expect talk of that move to color what will be relatively inflation-heavy PPI and CPI reports.Gurgling in the background is the looming end of the Fed's Quantitative Easing bond-buying program (QE2), which is scheduled to end in June. Also, debate about the Federal debt-ceiling limit will start to get more intense. Few doubt the debt-ceiling limit will get raised, but some fireworks are still expected as politicians jockey for advantage.After a frisson of fear and excitement, the market has returned to a somewhat happier place to start the week. But plenty of bogeymen continue to lurk, including the euro-zone debt crisis, the debate over the Federal debt ceiling and the coming end of QE2.L'Etoile du Nord-Dave KansasMARKET SNAP:At 6:10 a.m. EDT, S&P 500 futures are up 5.9 points, or 0.4%, at 1340.5. Dow futures are also 0.4% higher at 12621, while Nasdaq futures are 0.6% higher at 2388.3. European bourses are lower, however, weighed by debt concerns and lackluster earnings from banking giant HSBC. The FTSE 100 is off 0.6% at 5938.7, while Frankfurt's DAX is 0.9% lower at 7424.3. In Asia, stocks were mixed, with the Nikkei 225 down 0.7% at 9794.4 and the Hang Seng up 0.8% at 23336.0.Stocks to WatchAmong the companies whose shares are expected to actively trade in Monday's session are Artesian Resources Corp. (ARTNA), Fannie Mae (FNMA) and United Continental Holdings (UAL).Artesian Resources' first-quarter results fell short of analysts' estimates as the water, wastewater and engineering services provider's revenue decreased slightly year-over-year. Shares of Artesian Resources slipped 9.4% to $17.36 in light after-hours trading Friday.Fannie Mae's (FNMA) first-quarter loss narrowed sharply to $6.47 billion as the mortgage company benefited from significantly higher revenue.International Coal Group Inc. (ICO) said it has revised its first-quarter results due to an adverse verdict related to ongoing litigation with Allegheny Energy Supply. Due to the verdict, International Coal recorded a $40 million charge to its first-quarter earnings, resulting in a 3 cent loss per share compared with its previously announced 10 cent earnings per share.United Continental Holdings Inc.'s (UAL) traffic strengthened last month, reversing the trend of slowing growth or declines that the world's biggest airline had reported since combining operating data in October.Among the companies expected to report quarterly results early Monday are Tyson Foods Inc.
